  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Last year my score for CAT was around 40 percentile. What should I do to score > 90  percentile this year?",
  "response": "Improving your CAT score from around the 40 percentile to above 90 percentile is an ambitious but achievable goal. Here\u2019s a plan you can follow to help you reach your target:\n\n### 1. **Understand the Exam Structure**\n   - Familiarize yourself with the CAT exam pattern, which usually includes sections on Quantitative Ability (QA), Data Interpretation & Logical Reasoning (DILR), and Verbal Ability & Reading Comprehension (VARC).\n\n### 2. **Analyze Your Previous Performance**\n   - Review which areas you struggled in last year, whether it was certain types of questions, timing, or stress management.\n   - Identify your strong and weak subjects to strategize your preparation accordingly.\n\n### 3. **Create a Study Plan**\n   - Develop a structured study plan that allocates sufficient time for each section.\n   - Dedicate a few hours every day consistently over the months leading up to the exam.\n\n### 4. **Focus on Concepts**\n   - Strengthen your foundational concepts in all sections. Use standard textbooks and online resources to learn and practice.\n   - Break topics into manageable chunks and focus on one or two at a time.\n\n### 5. **Practice Regularly**\n   - Solve previous years' question papers and take mock tests. This will help with time management and familiarization with the exam format.\n   - Aim to simulate actual test conditions when taking mocks to gauge your performance accurately.\n\n### 6. **Work on Speed and Accuracy**\n   - Practice timed quizzes and work on questions that challenge your speed.\n   - Review wrong answers to understand mistakes and avoid repeating them.\n\n### 7. **Improve Reading Skills**\n   - For the VARC section, read newspapers, books, and articles regularly to enhance comprehension and speed.\n   - Practice summarizing what you read to reinforce understanding.\n\n### 8. **Focus on Data Interpretation and Logical Reasoning**\n   - Work on different types of graphs, charts, and logic puzzles regularly.\n   - Dedicate time to practicing various sets of DILR to improve your analytical skills.\n\n### 9. **Join Study Groups or Coaching**\n   - Consider joining a coaching institute or a study group for structured guidance and peer support.\n   - Engaging with fellow aspirants can provide motivation and valuable insights.\n\n### 10. **Stay Healthy and Manage Stress**\n   - Maintain a balanced diet, exercise regularly, and ensure adequate sleep.\n   - Practice relaxation techniques, such as meditation or yoga, to manage stress effectively.\n\n### 11. **Review and Revise**\n   - Set aside time for regular revision. Go through topics periodically to reinforce your learning.\n   - Focus on areas that need improvement based on mock test performance.\n\n### 12. **Stay Positive and Persistent**\n   - Stay motivated throughout your preparation. Set small, achievable targets, and celebrate your progress.\n   - Remember that consistency is key\u2014maintain your study routine and keep pushing yourself.\n\n### Final Thoughts\nImproving from 40 to over 90 percentile in the CAT requires dedication and systematic efforts. Stick to your study plan, assess your progress regularly, and adjust your strategy as needed. Good luck with your preparation!",
